<TITLE> Tigers bowlers struggle </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 5 (bdnews24.com)  The Bangladesh bowlers toiled on the second day of the three-day warm-up match against West Indies A as the home side fought back to take a 52-run lead at the close at the Kensington Oval, Bridgetown in Barbados on Saturday. Devon Thomas struck an unbeaten maiden first-class century to guide West Indies A to 247-8 at stumps in reply to Bangladesh's first innings total of 195 all out. The home team, who resumed the day on 82-4, fought back after being reduced to 147-6, to end the day 52 runs ahead when rain stopped play. When play began Thomas was yet score a run, but in an innings that lasted four hours he remained 105 not out off 194 balls and supported his captain Sewnarine Chattergoon, who fell for 50 when he was lbw to off-spinner Mahmud Ullah playing across the line. All-rounder Kevin McClean remained unbeaten on 21 along with Thomas when the bails were drawn for the second day. Pacer Shahadat Hossain (3-54) and Shakib Al Hasan (3-72) took three wickets each while Mahmud Ullah Riad grabbed two wickets. Mashrafe Bin Mortaza had to be satisfied with his previous two scalps. Bangladesh will play West Indies on Thursday in the first Test and will look to utilise the final day of the tour match to gain some form. bd
